1572	\leanok
1573	  Let \((R, \mathfrak{m})\) be regular of dimension \(d\) and pick a minimal generating set
1574	  \(x_1, \dots, x_d\) of \(\mathfrak{m}\). By Stacks tag 00NQ (lemma-regular-domain), \(R\) is
1575	  an integral domain, so \(x_1\) is a non-zero-divisor. The quotient \(R/x_1 R\) is a Noetherian
1576	  local ring of dimension \(\geq d - 1\) (by Krull's principal ideal theorem,
1577	  \texttt{lemma-one-equation}) with maximal ideal generated by \(x_2, \dots, x_d\), hence
1578	  has dimension exactly \(d - 1\) and is again regular of dimension \(d - 1\). Inducting on \(d\),
1579	  \(x_1, \dots, x_d\) is an \(R\)-regular sequence, so
1580	  \(\text{depth}(R) \geq d\). The reverse inequality \(\text{depth}(R) \leq \dim(R) = d\)
1581	  always holds for any nonzero finite module over a Noetherian local ring
1582	  (Stacks tag 00LK, \texttt{lemma-bound-depth}). Thus \(\text{depth}(R) = d = \dim(R)\), i.e.\
1583	  \(R\) is Cohen--Macaulay.
