1585	  \emph{Remark on the Auslander--Buchsbaum route.} The same conclusion can be obtained from
1586	  \cref{thm:auslander_buchsbaum} as follows: take \(M := R\) itself. Then \(M\) is
1587	  finitely generated and projective (free of rank \(1\)), so \(\text{pd}_R(R) = 0\). The
1588	  formula gives \(\text{depth}(R) = 0 + \text{depth}(R)\), a tautology. The non-tautological
1589	  use of Auslander--Buchsbaum is rather: for a regular local ring of dimension \(d\), every
1590	  finitely generated module \(M\) has \(\text{pd}_R(M) \leq d\) (Stacks tag 00O2,
1591	  \texttt{proposition-finite-gl-dim-regular}); applying the formula to such an \(M\) then
1592	  relates \(\text{depth}(M)\) to \(d - \text{pd}_R(M)\), which is the form most often used in
1593	  practice. The direct regular-sequence argument above is the cleanest proof of
1594	  \(R\) Cohen--Macaulay itself.
1595	\end{proof}
